  "why": "DistXplore assumes and enforces input validity using conservative, per-mutation constraints (e.g., L_p-based validity checks and bounded image transformations) and demonstrates high empirical validity rates, so it enforces semantic consistency/naturalness at the step-to-step mutation level. However, the method does not describe any mechanism that controls cumulative distortion relative to the original seed (e.g., fixing semantically-critical content or explicitly constraining similarity to the original seed across iterations). The search optimizes distributional objectives (MMD) for test suites rather than tracking/limiting accumulated change from the original seeds, and mutations are applied iteratively in a GA (mutating produced chromosomes), which allows per-step constraints but not explicit prevention of drift over many iterations. These facts align with the metric's definition of “Medium”: controls similarity/realism between successive steps but does not account for cumulative distortion across iterations.",
